Machine Learning for Investing and Trading¶

Background¶

Investment banks, hedge funds - even individual investors - develop financial models to predict price movements in publicly-traded securities. Successfully anticipating these movements can prove highly profitable for the investor; at the same time, a misstep could spell financial ruin. Historical stock prices provide a treasure trove of data, which may be suitable for machine learning algorithms to predict future stock price movements and - ultimately - drive more well-informed investment decisions. In this work, we build a stock price predictor that predicts stock price movements - specifically whether a price will rise or fall - based on historical performance.

We'll look at a few of the most valuable companies in the world, as measured by total market capitalization (market cap), spanning several industries:

  • Tesla (TSLA, automotive)
  • Johnson & Johnson (JNJ, pharmaceutical)
  • The Coca-Cola Company (KO, beverage)
  • Apple (AAPL, electronics)
  • ExxonMobile (XOM, energy / oil & gas)
  • JPMorgan Chase (JPM, financial services)

For comparative metrics (e.g., price movements relative to the overall market, which is captured in a parameter referred to as beta), we'll use an extremely popular index fund, the SPDR S&P 500 ETF (SPY, or "Spyder"), which invests in the entire S&P 500 index.

Exploration¶

To start, we'll look at a single stock—Tesla—along with the SPY index fund to get a feel for financial data and build intuition for what inputs may be useful in building out a predictive machine learning model.

Data types look right for Open, High, Low, Close, Adj Close, and Volume. We'll want to change the datatype for Date from string to datetime.

Process the data with some common financial analysis metrics to generate a new dataframe, which will be used in the machine learning model. The following features will be used (additional examples are mentioned here, and elaborated further in its own references):

  • Simple Moving Price Average: Average stock price over the prior n days; several different lagging periods will be used: 1 day (or—simply—the previous day's closing price), 1 week (n=5), 1 month (n=21, i.e., the average number of trading days in a month), and 1 quarter (n = 63, i.e., the average number of trading days in a quarter).
  • Moving Compount Returns: Compound returns over the prior n days, using the same lag periods as above.
  • Rolling Beta: Correlation of the stock price with the market index for the same lag periods as above (except for 1 day, which is meaningless from a correlation standpoint).
  • Momemntum Indicator: Stock price momentum (Ref), calculated using the same lag periods as above. Momentum is calculated simply as the current stock price less the stock price n periods prior: $M = P - P_{n}$
  • Stochastic Oscillator: A stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator comparing a particular closing price of a security to a range of its prices over a certain period of time (Ref). The oscillator is calculated as follows, where K is the current value of the stochastic indicator, C is the current price, $L_{14}$ is the lowest price over the past 14 trading periods, and $H_{14}$ is the highest price over the past 14 trading periods.
$$K = \frac{(C - L_{14})}{(H_{14} - L_{14})}*100$$
  • Fast Stochastic Indicator: Simple 3-period moving average of the Stochastic Oscillator.
  • Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD): MACD is a trend-following momentum indicator that shows the relationship between two moving averages of a security’s price, calculated by subtracting the 26-period Exponential Moving Average (EMA) from the 12-period EMA (Ref).

In practice, each indicator will be offset by one trading day in order to predict movements in the stock.

Finally, the target values will be converted into a binary output. While it is impossible to predict the actual future price, we may have better luck predicting whether the price will move up or down, so this will be the goal of the machine learning model.

In [6]:
def process(stock,market):
    
    '''
    This function takes as input raw stock data (Open, High, Low, and Adjusted Close prices and trading volume) for
    a single stock along with market reference data, processes the data with minimal analysis (e.g., to generate data
    for rate of return and beta), and returns the processed data for use in a machine learning algorithm.
    
    Input: raw stock price and volume data 

    Output: features and targets ready for use in ML applications
    '''
    
    # instantiate dataframe 
    df = stock.copy()

    # define periods that will be used for rolling / lagging indicators
    periods = [1,5,21,62]
    
    # ADD COLUMNS a priori to df

    for p in periods:
        
        # Simple Moving Price Average (SMA_n)
        df['SMA_{}'.format(str(p))] = stock['Close'].rolling(p).mean()
    
        # Simple Moving Price Returns (Ret_n)
        df['Ret_{}'.format(str(p))] = ((stock['Close']/stock['Open']-1).rolling(p).mean())
    
        # Rolling Beta
        df['Beta_{}'.format(str(p))] = (stock['Close']/stock['Open']-1).rolling(p).corr(market['Close']/market['Open']-1)
            
        # Momemntum Indicator (M_n)
        df['M_{}'.format(str(p))] = stock['Close'] - stock['Close'].shift(p)
    
    # Stochastic Oscillator
    df['Oscillator'] = (stock['Close'] - stock['Low'].shift(-14))/(stock['High'] - stock['Low'].shift(-14))
    
    # Fast Stochastic Indicator
    df['Indicator'] = df['Oscillator'].rolling(3).mean()
    
    # Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)
    df['MACD'] = stock['Close'].ewm(span=12).mean() - stock['Close'].ewm(span=26).mean()
    
    # Target: 1 = rise in stock price, 0 = fall in stock price 
    df['Target'] = (stock['Close'] - stock['Open']) > 0
    df['Target'].replace({True:1,False:0},inplace=True)
    
    # Drop 1 day rolling beta, which is meaningless
    df.drop('Beta_1',axis=1,inplace=True)
    
    # Convert Date to datetime datatype
    df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])

    # Fill inf with nan and nan values by first using forward, then backfill to avoid "looking into the future" bias
    df.replace(np.inf, np.nan,inplace=True)    
    df.replace(-np.inf, np.nan,inplace=True)
    df.fillna(method='ffill',inplace=True)
    df.fillna(method='bfill',inplace=True)

    return df

def get_features(df,shift):
    X = df.drop(['Date','Open','High','Low','Close','Adj Close','Volume','Target'],axis=1)
    Y = df.iloc[:,[-1]].shift(shift)
    Y.fillna(method='bfill',inplace=True)
    
    return X, Y

Build some intuition on the above¶

There's not much to be said about the simple moving average. It merely smooths the volatility in the price of the security and does so in a lagging manner. Some argue that the monthly or quarterly moving average is a more true indicator of the underlying value of a stock and that when a stock price exceeds two standard deviations from this price, it may be a strong buy or sell signal.

The smoothed return data don't tell us much. The number of positive and negative movements for tesla were roughly the same and the stock ended the period around the same price as the beginning of the period, so we would expect that the longer the perioed used in the average, the smoother and closer to zero, which is what we observe.

Momentum is the empirically observed tendency for rising asset prices to rise further, and falling prices to keep falling. For instance, it was shown that stocks with strong past performance continue to outperform stocks with poor past performance in the next period. Momentum can be caluated for an arbitrary period. From our analysis, we can see that the longer the period used to calculate this indicator, the more variability is shown in the data. It is interesting to note that for the 1 quarter momentum period, once the stock momentum started to change direction, it tended to continue until eventually reversing (i.e., the volatility was further spread out than for the shorter momentum periods). This aspect could be interesting to explore as a potential signal for a trading strategy as well as for predicting future binary changes (i.e., rise or fall) in stock prices, which we'll look at below.

Finally, as with returns, the beta value smooths over time and settles near the overall correlation value (which we calcuated at 0.53, abobve, for the entire period) for the quarterly rolling beta.

We'll first test the machine learning algorithm with all factors, below; then we'll remove some of the factors that at first glance appear to be largely noise (e.g., the shorter rolling beta periods) to see whether this improves our predictive capabilities.

Before that, though, let's look at the final few indicators: the oscillator indicators and MACD.

As noted above, the stochastic indicator is a momentum indicator comparing a particular closing price of a security to a range of its prices over a certain period of time. Momentum is relatively constant, save for a few instances where the price 14 days (the period used in the indicator) apart is nearly the same, which generates spikes in the indicator (and therefore a change in the direction of the momentum.

Finally, the MACD is designed to reveal changes in the strength, direction, momentum, and duration of a trend in a stock's price. It is primarily used as a tool to guide trading strategies, but we'll see how useful it is in predicting price movements.

Machine Learning Model¶

Next, let's run the machine learning model. We'll use a random forest classifier with a grid search over a few key hyperparameters (the number of estimators, minimum samples per split, and minimum samples per leaf); we'll also look at how good of a job we can do predicting price movements further out into the future—between one day and one month ahead.

Before we dig in, an aside on how we'll be doing the cross-validation. It's not appropriate to do random train-test splits or conventional k-fold cross-validation on time series data, as doing so leaks data from the future into the model (i.e., these approaches future-bias the model). It also doesn't make sense to use some amount of historical data to predict a subset of more recent data in a single shot, as that introduces recency bias. Time series split is an alternative approach. This method entails dividing the training set into two folds at each iteration, ensuring that the validation set is always ahead of the training split. The following block of code illustrates this appraoch with the Tesla data.

In [21]:
splits = 4

for split in range(1,splits+1):
    lim  = int(split/splits*len(df))
    idx  = int(0.75*lim)

    
    train = df.iloc[:lim][['Date','Close']]
    train.rename(columns = {'Close':'Train'},inplace=True)

    test  = df.iloc[idx:lim,:][['Date','Close']]
    test.rename(columns = {'Close':'Test'},inplace=True)

    data = train.merge(test,left_on='Date',right_on='Date',how='outer')

    ax = data.plot(x='Date',y=['Train','Test'],figsize=(20,2),linewidth=4)
    ax.set_xlim([735600,737371])
    ax.legend(fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Price ($/share)',fontsize=18)
    
    for tick in ax.yaxis.get_major_ticks():
        tick.label.set_fontsize(16)        

    if split == 1:
        ax.set_title('Demonstration of Time Series Train-Test-Split',fontsize=30)
        
    if split != splits:
        ax.set_xticklabels([])
        ax.set_xlabel('')
        
    if split == splits:
        ax.tick_params(axis="x", labelsize=16,rotation=0)
        ax.set_xlabel('Date',fontsize=24)

periods = 22

results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Company','Period','Accuracy','Random Chance','min_samples_leaf', 'min_samples_split', 'n_estimators'])


for p in range(1,periods):
    start = time.time()

    for stock in stocks:
        df = process(stock,SPY)
        X, Y = get_features(df,p)

        model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=5)

        param_search = {'n_estimators': [25,100,250],
                        'min_samples_split': [2, 10, 20],
                        'min_samples_leaf': [2, 10, 20]}

        tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)
        gsearch = GridSearchCV(estimator = model,
                               cv = tscv,
                               param_grid = param_search)

        gsearch.fit(X,Y.values.ravel())

        best = gsearch.best_score_* 100.0
        leaf = gsearch.best_params_['min_samples_leaf']
        samp = gsearch.best_params_['min_samples_split']
        ests = gsearch.best_params_['n_estimators']

        results.loc[len(results)] = [stock.name, p, best, Y.mean()[0]*100, leaf, samp, ests]

    print('Period {} run time: '.format(str(p)).ljust(20),'{}s'.format(round(time.time()-start,1)))

Review results¶

As noted above, there are some indicators that appear little more than noise. In the following, we'll select a curated list, guided by intuition more than anything, to see if we can improve upon these results (an alternative approach would be to build the model by systemating adding or removing factors to guague the predictive capabilities of each factor and select the set that does best). Here, we'll try an intuitive approach, using the following indicators:

  • All simple moving averages
  • Quarterly rolling average for momentum, beta, and returns
  • 3-day average stochastic oscillator indicator
  • MACD

    print('Period {} run time: '.format(str(p)).ljust(20),'{}s'.format(round(time.time()-start,1)))

It looks like our intuition wasn't too helpful in improving accuracy—the second version of the model lost ground in accuracy, especially for the first few prediction intervals, but also for the longer term.

Concluding thoughts¶

The market generally trends up, so the further out you look, the more likely it is that the market will go up based on the underlying trend (i.e., we invest because we expect the market to go up, and becuase we expect the market to go up, we invest, driving the cycle). Given this fact, it is a little surprising that the accuracy goes down in this model; that is, the model is not designed to capture this effect. More careful consideration of how the indicators are used to predict (i.e., we didn't actually use the underlying stock price itself as a feature, which may help in teasing out this trend). Nevertheless, our model does a beter job than random guessing— it's better than employing a strategy that always guesses increase, for example, but it doesn't necessarily guide an investment strategy. That's a topic for another day!
